igate challenges and capitalize on opportunities [Data: Concepts (1106); Relationships (1098)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Challenges of Non-Quantifiable Objectives\",\n            \"explanation\": \"One of the significant challenges in performance management is dealing with non-quantifiable objectives, especially in not-for-profit and public sector organizations. These objectives often relate to social, environmental, or community outcomes that are difficult to measure using traditional financial metrics. Addressing these challenges requires innovative approaches and qualitative measures to capture the true impact of an organization's activities [Data: Concepts (1103); Relationships (1095)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Issues with Multiple Objectives in Not-for-Profit Organizations\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Not-for-profit organizations often face the complexity of managing multiple objectives, which can complicate performance measurement and management. These objectives may include financial sustainability, social impact, and community engagement, among others. Balancing these diverse goals requires a nuanced approach to performance analysis that can accommodate the unique mission and values of not-for-profit organizations [Data: Concepts (1104); Relationships (1096)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Measuring Performance in Not-for-Profit Organizations\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Measuring performance in not-for-profit organizations involves considering their unique objectives and challenges. Traditional financial metrics may not fully capture the success of these organizations, necessitating the use of alternative measures such as social return on investment (SROI), impact assessments, and stakeholder feedback. These methods provide a more comprehensive view of an organization's performance and its contribution to societal goals [Data: Concepts (1105); Relationships (1097)].\"